        <bioghist id="ref8">
            <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
            <p>Alex (Alexander) Bittelman (1890-1982), a Communist activist and theoretician who was one of the founders of the Jewish Communist movement in the United States was born in Berdichev, Ukraine. He became a printer, joined the Jewish Labor Bund, was imprisoned in Kherson (Ukraine) and elsewhere for his revolutionary activity, and emigrated to the United States in 1912, where he joined the Jewish Socialist Federation. In 1919, he joined the fledgling Communist Party (CP) and became the head of its Jewish Federation. During the 1920s. Bittelman served on the Party’s Politburo and was an ally of William Z. Foster in CP factional struggles. During the 1930s he wrote for the Daily Worker and the Communist, the Party’s theoretical organ. During the 1940s he oversaw Party work among Jews. During the 1950s he was one of several Party leaders convicted of violating the Smith Act and served time in federal prison. In 1959 was expelled from the CPUSA.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref9">
            <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
            <p>The collection consists of an unpublished autobiography in 32 chapters describing childhood and radical activities in Russia; arrival in the United States in 1912; early Socialist connections; formation of the American Communist Party; factional feuds within the Communist movement; comments on its important personalities; including Earl Browder; William Z. Foster; Jay Lovestone; Charles E. Ruthenberg, and many others; travels to the Soviet Union; reflections on the New Deal and Cold War; thoughts on Bittelman's imprisonment for Communist activities; concern for Jewish survival; and general reflections.</p>
        </scopecontent>
